<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911125-0059</DOCNO><DOCID>911125-0059.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media Brief -- News Corp.:   Banks Commit to Extend   Over $3.2 Billion of Loans</HL><DATE>11/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   NWS</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)PUBLISHING, INFORMATION SERVICES COMPANIES (PUB)</IN><NS>FINANCING AGREEMENTS (FNC)</NS><RE>AUSTRALIA (ASA)FAR EAST (FE)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)</RE><LP>   News Corp. said it received commitments from its majorbank lenders to extend in excess of $3.2 billion of its loansfor an additional three-year period, starting February 1994.The media concern said it is continuing its talks to increasethe amount of loans to be extended.   News Corp. said its major lenders have also agreed toprovide it with greater flexibility with respect to paymentof dividends, making of investments and issuing long-termdebt securities.</LP><TEXT>   News Corp. is in the process of raising about $450 millionin new equity and $250 million in new debt as part of afinancial reorganization designed to reduce its debt load,strengthen its financial position and add to working capital.Earlier this month, News Corp. filed a registration statementfor new debt and equity offerings and agreements that includethe recently completed private placement of a 55% interest inNews Corp.'s Australian commercial printing and magazineoperations for about $500 million.</TEXT></DOC>